segments.text: This is Deborah Beale, and I am interviewing Dr. Spencer Beane on the history of Texas Engineering Experiment Station.
The date is June 6, 1984.
So the first thing, you did give a biographical statement in that one interview.
You had your fill in that one, so I was going to make you go through that again if you'd like to.
But I would like you to update some of the biography there.
At that time, you were...
they were just setting up no
Since this is an update of the oral history that we have, I'll just kind of correct that.
I had already been the director over here at the Center for International Support, and I had been hand-in-hand, and I think it's probably worth it.
You've got the view in there that I...
It was just take over or something like that.
Well, they did, they had a little extra interest.
They were still successful students from that community.
Yes, at that time, it looked like I was going to be full-time here, which I didn't.
You could tell that.
Because I am an engineer.
My loyalty is to engineering.
My objective in life was to be an engineer and all those good things, and so I wanted to do it.
with the Ateez organization and who I am.
So that's the part that's really changed since 1981.
I've been a quarter-time engineering experiment station, three-quarter-time here at the Center.
And I continue to get involved
and serve God and get people active and get people to understand.
I hope a million things because I think that's what makes me very good.
I think we're solving problems.
We're involved in solving problems.
And there's students involved in solving problems and there are graduates because they're involved in solving problems.
How did you first become successful with these materials?
Well, I had a Ph.D. from Caltech in mechanical and electrical engineering in 1950.
I spent 20 years in the Army in their missile research development.
And in 1970, I was only 50 years old and decided that if I wanted to have a second career, I needed to be out of the Army.
So I was out of the Army.
And I didn't have a job.
But because of my Caltech degrees,
And they made me a real good offer, but at the same time living in Washington, D.C., living in that area.
for five years during my 20 years of research about the hectic nature of just getting to and from work.
And so we didn't want to move back to the Forks.
So I interviewed also in the University of Alabama in Huntsville.
I later moved here and I moved in Austin and I offered a job in Austin and I offered a job here.
And I could have had a job in El Paso, but I didn't want that.
And being an Aggie, I decided I wanted to come back to Texas A&M, come back home, and help develop a research program in Texas A&M.
And I've done quite well, and I'm saying because of me.
I feel like a part of it anyway.
Since 1970, our sponsored research program, our global research program, has really expanded.
It's gratifying.
I've been a part of all this.
Were you hired to be both assistant director and head of the space, or did one develop out of the other?
I was hired as an assistant director and head of space technology, but we didn't make a big deal out of things like that.
Things kind of grew.
I hit the ground, and as you read in Billy Hathorne, the first project I worked on had nothing to do with space.
It was the environmental aspects of the building and the amount of solar here.
And I kind of did what they did.
There weren't a whole lot of us at that time.
Mr. Benson was the dean of engineering and the director, and Harriet Whitmore was the associate director, and there was me.
And then we had a fiscal officer as well, who was part legal.
Mr. Fenner and Mr. Whitmore and myself and Mr. Henson.
We just did what we needed to do.
We managed to stay busy and active and we managed to get other people impacted and involved.
So I would say that the Kresge organization was involved over the many years starting in 1940.
I mean, Spence thought that the industries and urban populations of the state of Texas really needed some technical help, as well as the rural people being in the Gulf.
I mean, it's evolved.
I think that the real growth, indeed, started with Harry Whitson in 1963, because Harry had been
Army research and development also means familiar with how contracting is done and the administrative aspects of that.
Plus, being an A&M in the core, you learn the need for organization.
You learn in the Army the need for authority and organization, follow-up, and the formality requirements of contracting.
So I think that our main growth has come since the 1960s.
And then it's like I said, we're most of the shuttle research grants.
You read that in there.
It was $15,000 total.
That's all we had.
And I guess in the final analysis, we've done about the same thing.
of shuttle related work.
We're still doing shuttle related work.
So it's good that the folks in that program have confidence in them and confidence in our researchers.
That's what makes success.
And A&M will be successful as long as they can deliver quality results and get people that want to do quality research.
Who did you deal with inside and outside of the team?
Everybody.
Everybody?
Anybody and everybody that wanted to be involved in some research or we thought we needed for some research.
Like the Navasol project, we have 45 professionals from all over the university.
And they were involved in an extensive conference, one-week conference.
And then later, the consultant started to play, to read the final report.
To my knowledge, that was the first major participant in the project that anyone else had.
You had direct access to it.
You didn't have to go through your pay.
I never... An organization, in my mind, is something that is a guide for people to have a home in the first place.
But if you need to get outside your organization, do it.
You've got to know other people outside your organization.
You can't look internally at them.
Because many of the complex problems today require expertise from veterinary homes, effects of lasers on the eyes, effects of chemicals, toxicants, and so forth, from humans and animals.
It's got to involve a lot of other people to do all the work.
Have the administrations at A&M been helpful in letting you do that in a timely manner?
Well, we get along.
And any organization, as complex as A&M, any organization will work if people want to work.
And if people want to work together, they will work together, in spite of problems, in spite of bureaucracy, in spite of administrative hang-ups and regulations that says thou shall not.
You can still use those regulations as a guide to the norm, but if you have to make an exception and you have to get an exception, go get it.
If you just accept no's all the time, you don't go anywhere.
You have to accept the challenges.
I'll just use a good example.
The court happens to be sitting on my desk right now.
And it just happened to be there because I haven't seen it since.
This project evolved from one of our projects, or a number of our projects, in December of 2011.
Center for Environmental Resources is an organization that serves throughout the university system.
We have projects with Tom and Alex, and we have projects with Prairie View, Forest Service, and the Coastal Recruitment Station.
Wherever a researcher is who wants to do something,
And if we can help him with small amounts of money, or providing him with contacts with sponsors and outside organizations, or help him just develop an inquisitiveness into a subject, we do it.
The project that I'm looking at is a $500,000 a year project for three years in the agricultural and family space.
And Dr. Hyler is the principal investigator and has a contract with the Gas Research Institute.
And as I said, many of the parts of this project came from
those seed projects, those encouragements that we've given to researchers, not only in agriculture, but in engineering.
They've got guys on here from engineering who are participating, Guy Curry, an engineer, an industrial engineer, system engineering,
We have, uh, helping these people also are folks from .
But here's an example of cooperation that has paid off.
All of these researchers, and this researcher, I think they're, uh, uh, like 19 researchers in a separate project.
And it's a good thing because, uh,
It's looking at new alternate resources for the future, new ways of developing crops to produce energy, things like gas, natural gas, in the case of gas recertification.
But you can't always stay within your own organization with a crop.
We've got to get people from other disciplines involved.
Is that what TEAS has been all about since you came here?
TEAS has been growing in a lot of different ways.
A lot of our projects have been interdisciplinary and based on cooperation with others.
We've had projects with them at college, and with agriculture, and with science, and, you know, sometimes that doesn't go anywhere for people to work with.
But they've got to want to work with you, or they will not.
It's a matter of developing that attitude.
Has that attitude improved or stayed the same pretty much since you've been here, or has it gotten worse?
Well, right at the present time, we're having some organizational difficulties.
We've got people starting to sit and wait.
I would say that right at the present time, we are at some crossroads.
People have got to want to work, do research, and they've got to want to do it within the system that exists.
Or they spend their time in a wasteful circle, fighting the system.
And I don't like that.
I think people...
with a can-do attitude, wanting to do things, are going to find ways to make the organization work.
I mean, any organization will work if people want to.
And I'm upset about that.
Because we've got people who are wasting time arguing about it.
Is that something that's happened on and off since you've been here, or is this a new development?
Well, there's always been some of that.
There are always people.
University is a unique place because there are unique people.
There are all kinds of people.
There are some people who are going to stand up and argue against anything and everything.
And then there are going to be those on the other end who are going to stand up and fight for everything.
Some people are naive.
Some people are positive.
Some people want to do research.
Some people don't want to do research.
Some people think that research detracts from their scholastic achievements.
Some other people think that research is essential.
to their development and to their achievement in the human profession.
And there's all a great spectrum of people in the world, all classes, all kinds.
And it's a real challenge to present opportunities to do things through this broad spectrum and see the different responses that you get from people.
I think that psychologists,
But it's a big role in university research.
And that's where I spend most of my time, I guess I should say, on doing just that.
I have given seminars.
I've considered teaching in mechanical engineering.
It's a part-time job.
I've worked in the M.T.
's administration.
I've worked with air in the plane.
I've worked with all the federal agencies and all the quasi-agencies.
Yes, we're a research institute.
I decided I'd just take it, but I didn't have the time to do that.
Try to teach a bunch of students and then you have to leave town and not do a good job.
I didn't teach.
Trying to find opportunities for people to do research.
And many times being disappointed by not being able to find people to do research on projects where there was a great opportunity outside.
But that's the way things go.
Well, my attitude is
that students were on the future of this nation and trained and empowered by our first reason for being here.
And I think I've adopted the attitude that I've heard written by many people, including Bill, and all these other associations, the National Science Foundation, the U.S. National Science Foundation,
The attitude seems to be developing that a good university must be involved in research.
And that if A&M is to be an outstanding university, its professors must be involved, its students must be involved.
So my attitude has been that
A, our first loyalty, our first purpose for being is the student.
But then in turn, the professors are the professors.
And the students are better than
graduates if they've been involved in a research project, because then they learn that continued success depends upon producing acceptable results.
And it's all part of a training for a leadership role in the future.
I was involved for many years with the co-op.
I think it's an excellent, excellent opportunity for a youngster, regardless of his financial status, to get an education and learn the outside world at the same time.
Many times, the industries that hire that go out during the alternate periods end up hiring them for a long time .
And the student's happier working for a company that he knows, and the company's happier because they know the student because he's worked for them.
But I was very much involved in that when we were closer together with the College of Engineering.
I have the, on the steak prize, industrial sponsors would provide the steaks.
And the wives of the faculty, and the team's wives too, would bring cakes and different vegetables and things.
And we'd have a picnic out in the park, the pencil park or over there.
right at the center or wherever.
And I would get the students together and say, okay, now you go get the stakes, and you go get the wood for the fire, and you go get the tongs, and you go get this.
And we'd get over there a couple hours early and we'd cut those stakes up and get them ready and took them.
We had a lot of fun.
In fact, we got together a lot.
And I think those sorts of things

I did this sort of thing, and I participated with the American Society of Engineering Education, and was on the Engineering Research Council for a year, because I felt like I needed to know the faculty.
I needed to interact with the faculty.

They needed to know me, so I involved myself in a co-op program that Texas Society of Education was doing here, and the American Association of Engineering Advancing the Core of Engineering Education.
And all those sort of things.
So, I've enjoyed it.
I love it.
I love it.
I want to continue to have that baggy spirit.
Stand together.
It's the heavy thing.
So will any arguments about organization make me upset?
Because I think we can continue our progress and make these organizations work.
We want to.
And as Aggies by and large, we've got to work.
We've got to have a solid force.
We've got to produce.
Because we're going to be successful if we do.
The Center for Energy and Mineral Resources is not a part of TEES.
It's a university line item in the budget.
It's not administered by TEES?
No, it is not part of TEES at all.
It is not part of TEES at all.
It is completely separate from TEES.
But it has a total system-wide responsibility.
And as long as that continues, I'm happy.
If somebody wants to say, now you can't give any projects to engineering.
You can't give any to agriculture, because they're already there.
or funded organization that eliminates developing people who have the potential of really doing something.
Because in a larger organization, a lot of times the man's eyes don't get understood.
Maybe we can help them be heard, be understood.
Then they can shine.
The keys can profit.
That guy, big research project.
Agriculture, big research project.
And so I think that CEMR,
It brings forth to me that A&M is a real strong company.
The mid-1970s energy crisis, did that bring on a squirt of money and funds for energy research?
Well, it brought on the legislature supporting this center, which was started in 75.
Did Keith get involved in that type of research as well?
Well, Keith is involved in that.
A lot of the researchers over there are doing engineering.
You can talk to some engineers and say everything that engineers do is engineering-based.
If you're working on an engine, you're trying to make it more efficient.
If you're working on a chemical process, you're trying to make it more efficient, energy-wise.
All the chemical processes use natural gas for oil and for aerobics and electronics.
Electrical engineering.
generation of electricity is mostly by fossil fuel.
That's got to be more efficient.
So everything that the engineers do
whether it be robotics, manufacturing engineering, is involved in .
Yes, I'd say that the energy related work in engineering and in agriculture and in many parts of the system needs 75%.
Have you found in your working with Tease that there's been, Tease has seen the problems before, at least the legislature or a lot of other people, the problems that need to be addressed?
Well, I think we think more through the future than the legislators do sometimes.

And I think that given the resources that the legislature gives to TEAS allows TEAS to reflect on the future and to be involved in all these outside organizations and to be able to assess some of the future needs of the country and to start
start getting together capabilities to help solve some of those kinds of problems or some of those kinds of developments, do some exploratory work.
You see, the TEAS professors are a faculty member.
A lot of them are doing basic research, fundamental research.
I remember doing a lot of research, solving problems in a short period of time.
But others are looking at, why does this do this?
And it's a longer term payoff.
It may not even be payoff.
It's basic research.
You don't know what the end result is going to be like.
It might be a new design for a new car.
Completely different from the configuration of the ones we've had in the past.
They might fly the shuttle backwards instead of with the nose pointed forward.
Or somebody comes up with a new theory that this has to happen.
Everybody says it won't work.
And some guy goes out and makes it work.
I don't like people who have negative attitudes.
I've already judged that.
And I know people who say it can't be done.
Because if you say that somebody can't do something, you're not bringing them up.
Maybe a new theory will come.
What I'm saying is that the engineering researchers are involved in the basic studies of what I think both of them need.
And A&M, I think, has built its reputation based upon practical
engineers, practical graduates, practical managers of the future.
I think that Ford at one time sent a vice president out there and down here to look at A&M and find out why is A&M, why are A&M graduates good?
Why do we have 34 in our top S and bottom three?
Why are 34 good?
How do you go about finding the funds for it?
Well, it's a matter of salesmanship.
convincing people that Aggies will be willing to try.
We ran a workshop here for a gas research institute about three years ago.
And we, I think, sold it based upon the attitude that, well, it's a darn difficult task to do in such a short period of time.
But we're willing to undertake it.
And we will deliver it.
And we did deliver it.
It's like one, two, three, four.
We did finally deliver a quality product.
And as a result of good relationships with the National Research Institute, projects like this helped us.
Let me just say that TEAS is not just engineering.
TEES started out being basically engineering.
It's called the Engineering Experiment Study.
But now the College of Education is involved with TEES and UCI technology for education purposes.
Let's face it, satellites and microelectronics can play a part in disseminating information worldwide.
We have classrooms in Nairobi that use satellites.
But at any rate, education, liberal arts, geosciences, and who else?
I was thinking of you.
Well, we've got geosciences, liberal arts, business administration, business administration and education.
Or the four other colleges.
So about half of the colleges are now involved in TEAS research.
And in addition to that, TEAS is on an outreach type of program.
It's now a development program with Arlington, University of Texas at Arlington, cooperating in microelectronics and things like that, like research.
Are those cooperations at the instigation of TEAS, or are these organizations coming to TEAS and saying... Well, I think this first started with TEAS at the instigation.
But it just so happens that John Rouse, who's the Dean of Engineering up there, was the director of our own census team.

So he's fully familiar with the TEAS organization and that helped bring in the cooperative agreement, which was approved by our Board of Regents, by the University of Texas Board of Regents, so we cooperated in this research.
What about the different schools in A&M?
Are the new programs at the instigation of this little business that they can take?
In some cases, I think so.
Based upon Dr. Bill Mews' interest in bringing forth new opportunities for the professors in business administration, he, I think, got together with Skip Porter and decided
give professors over there in economics and whatever management opportunities to participate.
Where did he switch from what, and I'm not sure what the definition is, from technology research to high tech research?
Is there a difference?
There's not a difference.
Like
I mean it's a matter of definition.
Like basic research is a matter of definition.
What is basic research?
What is applied research?
Some of the research done over there in the Food Protein Research and Development Center using
diverse osmosis, different types of membranes, separating proteins of various lengths of chains and that sort of thing.
Well, it's applied, but you have to have some fundamental knowledge of what it is you're doing in order to make these membranes work.
And they've come up with some separation processes now that are going to revolutionize the food industry.
Whereas before we were throwing out a lot of it,
of ways and stuff that she's making, we're going to save all that stuff.
And that's going to cut down on the pollution requirements for waste treatment plants and save food stuff that makes the food industry more efficient.
One of the researchers over in the food protein research in Melbourne now has a patent that's with the Japanese involved.
And that's going to be very helpful to him
So what's the difference between tech and high tech?
Well, high technology right now is defined by many people as involving computers and solid state electronics.
Solid state electronics involves an integrated circuit
and making things smaller and smaller with larger and larger capacity.
The larger and larger the capacity of one of these chips makes a computer that much more capable.
And that's the high tech.
But biotechnology has also got a high tech flavor.
And in that case, they're taking cloning
cloning some of the DNA and the bio-chains and the genes are being split and put back together.
Things are just getting, just getting, I think, solid.
It's just really another term for progress.
I think so.
I think, you know, we had an information explosion many years ago.
We still got information.
Technology transfer is still one of our goals.
problems and racism, I'd say.

and then Windows replaced that and put it in a new format and hired some new people
and some quality writers and some artists who really have made it in the first class.
One of the shortfalls, I think, of our publications is that we are not real sure of our dissemination list or who to send it to.
People in important places who should get it change all the time, every time.
Organizations change.
And it's darn difficult to keep up with it.
I have the same problem over here.
We were sending out close to 10,000 copies of our Texas Energy newsletter that was published 10 times a year, and now it's published six times a year.
And we purged the list and started all over, and it went down to 3,500, and now we're back up to 1,500.
People read it.
Who would you be?
Are you sending out to industry and any other?
Industry, other schools, other researchers.
University of Texas sent us a copy of .
We try to outdo each other, and there's nothing wrong with competition.

It was a separate center, but a close connection .
Now I understand that we're going to sort of change the purpose of remote sensing.
And I have not had anything to do with this.
I'm against it.
I believe the remote sensing potential is only going to be scratched.
We will be doing many, many more things with remote sensing information, whether it be manufacturing processes, looking at Earth from space, looking at space from Earth, or whatever.
But it's now going to have the flavor of high tech, high level technologies.
It's going to be more centered than I like to call it.
Fantastic.

So neutron radiography is a very important thing.
More research into the problem.

and they have not aggressively gone out into the city, outside.
